The Creeper program from 1971 is often treated as the first self-replicating network program; it mostly just wandered around ARPANET announcing itself like a very smug pop-up.
Reaper was written to remove Creeper, which means one of the earliest security tools was effectively a worm sent to hunt another worm. Very on-brand for this industry.
The Morris Worm hit in 1988 and spread so aggressively that an experiment became a large-scale outage, infecting roughly 6,000 machines when the internet was still tiny enough for that to be catastrophic.
The Morris Worm helped trigger the creation of CERT, because once your network is on fire, “we should probably organise incident response” becomes less of a suggestion.
Early malware often spread by floppy disk, which meant “air gap” once had a natural predator called “someone with a pocket”.
The Brain virus, released in 1986, is often cited as the first widely known PC boot-sector virus and came from two brothers in Pakistan trying to track software piracy.
The AIDS Trojan from 1989 is widely remembered as an early ransomware ancestor; it was literally distributed on floppy disks to conference attendees, which is one way to ruin a delegate bag.
The term Trojan horse in computing stuck because the whole point is deception: look useful, do something else, and leave the user wondering when life choices stopped working.
John von Neumann’s work on self-reproducing automata long pre-dated modern malware, proving that computer scientists can accidentally foreshadow future security headaches decades in advance.
Long before phishing kits, phone phreakers abused telephone signalling systems to make free calls, showing that technical abuse and billing fraud were old friends before the internet arrived.
The famous “blue box” used in phone phreaking exploited signalling tones, which is a reminder that abusing trusted control channels is older than most current VPN concentrators.
Kevin Mitnick became one of the most famous hackers of the 1990s largely because he combined technical skill with social engineering, which remains an unhelpfully durable combo.
Cliff Stoll’s book The Cuckoo’s Egg turned a tiny accounting discrepancy into one of the best-known counter-espionage stories in computing history.
That same case showed a timeless truth: sometimes an intrusion starts with a tiny anomaly no one else has time for, until suddenly everyone has time for it.
The 1980s and 1990s saw antivirus vendors become household names, largely because malware authors kept providing the most aggressive possible product-market fit.
The Melissa macro virus in 1999 spread via infected Word documents, making office productivity tools productive in a way nobody wanted.
ILOVEYOU hit in 2000 with a subject line engineered to beat human judgement using curiosity, trust, and the universal weakness known as opening things we shouldn’t.
ILOVEYOU was written in VBScript, which gave the world another reason to look suspiciously at seemingly harmless script files.
Macro malware thrived because users trusted documents, and to be fair, “it’s just a file from someone I know” still causes trouble now.
Email worms taught defenders that message security is not just about blocking malware; it is about blocking persuasion at machine speed.
The Code Red worm in 2001 targeted Microsoft IIS servers and spread fast enough to make patching delays look like an open invitation.
Code Red II followed quickly, because malware naming can be almost as repetitive as organisations postponing maintenance windows.
The Nimda worm in 2001 spread in multiple ways at once, which made it memorable and miserable in roughly equal measure.
Nimda’s name is “admin” backwards, because malware authors have always enjoyed making bad situations slightly more annoying through naming choices.
The SQL Slammer worm in 2003 spread so quickly that it congested networks within minutes, despite being tiny enough to fit in a very smug paragraph of code.
SQL Slammer showed that payload size matters less than propagation speed when the internet is happy to assist with the rest.
The Blaster worm exploited Windows RPC and famously included a message aimed at Bill Gates, because some malware authors crave audience feedback.
Sasser spread without email or user clicks, proving again that if patching is late enough, the network will do the distribution work for the attacker.
The Conficker worm from 2008 infected millions of systems and was so persistent that it inspired one of the most coordinated industry clean-up efforts of its time.
Conficker used multiple propagation methods, including weak passwords, which means it succeeded through both technical flaw and human optimism.
The Zeus banking trojan became notorious for credential theft and spawned countless descendants, because malware families reproduce faster than change control.
Zeus also helped popularise the idea of malware-as-a-service long before every SaaS company started promising to “transform your workflow”.
SpyEye even marketed itself against Zeus, which briefly made cybercrime look like a particularly grim startup rivalry.
Stuxnet was discovered in 2010 and changed cyber history by demonstrating malware that could cause physical damage to industrial equipment, not just digital chaos.
Stuxnet specifically targeted industrial control logic tied to Iranian centrifuges, showing that malware could sabotage hardware while reporting that everything was fine.
One reason Stuxnet stunned researchers was its apparent use of multiple zero-days, which is not a cheap hobby unless a nation-state budget is nearby.
Countdown to Zero Day by Kim Zetter became one of the definitive books on Stuxnet because the story is too bizarre to be left to rumour alone.
The documentary Zero Days also helped drag Stuxnet into mainstream awareness, proving that industrial sabotage can, in fact, make it into film recommendations.
Stuxnet is often described as the first true cyberweapon to cause physical destruction, which is an awkward milestone for the security timeline.
Stuxnet also taught defenders that PLCs and engineering workstations are not magically safe just because the average office worker has never heard of them.
Duqu was linked to Stuxnet through code similarities and appeared more focused on espionage, because even malware ecosystems have spin-offs.
Flame was remarkable for its complexity and espionage capability, with features more like a Swiss Army knife than a single-purpose implant.
Flame could record audio, capture screenshots, and harvest data, showing that “surveillance platform” is sometimes the more accurate label than “virus”.
Gauss, another espionage-focused malware family from the same era, reportedly targeted financial information and Middle Eastern systems, because regional campaigns often mix politics and money.
Shamoon wiped data and hit Saudi Aramco in 2012, reminding defenders that not every major attack is about encryption or theft; sometimes destruction is the point.
Wiper malware is especially nasty because you cannot negotiate with deleted files, however persuasive your procurement team may be.
CryptoLocker helped make ransomware a household term by weaponising public key encryption in a way that made recovery a budgeting problem.
Before ransomware became industrialised, many people still thought backups were boring. They remain boring, just dramatically more important.
Gameover Zeus combined banking malware with botnet operations, showing attackers love platform strategies too.
The takedown of botnets often looks like modern whack-a-mole: seize infrastructure, celebrate briefly, watch the ecosystem regrow somewhere annoying.
A botnet is just a criminally managed fleet of compromised devices, proving that distributed systems are not automatically noble.
The Mirai botnet rose to fame by recruiting insecure IoT devices with default credentials, which was effectively the internet being punished for “admin/admin”.
Mirai’s 2016 DDoS attacks disrupted major services and highlighted how cheap internet-connected rubbish can become expensive internet-connected trouble.
One enduring Mirai lesson is that cameras, DVRs, and routers are computers with feelings, and those feelings are usually “no one patched me”.
DDoS attacks do not need stealth to be effective; brute-force volume is often enough when defenders are trying to distinguish traffic from weather.
Dyn’s 2016 outage showed how hitting infrastructure providers can ripple into much wider internet disruption than the target list might suggest.
The WannaCry outbreak in May 2017 spread globally by exploiting SMB flaws and left hospitals, businesses, and public services dealing with encrypted systems and very bad mornings.
WannaCry used the EternalBlue exploit, a reminder that once offensive capability leaks, defenders inherit the maintenance nightmare.
One of the most repeated WannaCry details is that the outbreak was slowed by a registered kill-switch domain, which is not a cyber strategy anyone wants to rely on twice.
The NHS impact made WannaCry especially visible because cyber incidents feel more real when medical systems stop being background plumbing and start being headline news.
NotPetya in 2017 looked like ransomware but behaved more like a wiper, turning recovery into a cruel joke for anyone hoping payment might help.
NotPetya spread through compromised software updates and network movement, making trusted distribution channels part of the blast radius.
Many researchers call NotPetya one of the most financially destructive cyberattacks ever, because collateral damage scaled far beyond the original intended geography.
Calling something “ransomware” does not mean decryption is possible; sometimes the note is decorative cruelty attached to sabotage.
M.E.Doc, the Ukrainian software update channel used in NotPetya, became the textbook example of supply-chain compromise done with devastating efficiency.
Supply-chain attacks work because defenders spend years teaching users to trust updates, then attackers turn up wearing a release note.
SolarWinds became security shorthand in 2020 for the nightmare scenario where a trusted software supplier pushes compromise downstream at scale.
The SolarWinds intrusion highlighted just how much modern enterprise trust is delegated through build systems, signing processes, and update mechanisms.
Supply-chain compromise is especially dangerous because it piggybacks on what blue teams are trying to preserve: normal operations.
Kode frauds and payment scams often succeed not by breaking cryptography, but by breaking confidence, timing, and process. Humans remain wonderfully scriptable.
Magecart became the go-to label for web skimming groups that injected malicious JavaScript into online shops, effectively turning checkout pages into card-harvesting farms.
Web skimming proved that you do not always need to breach the buyer if you can quietly squat in the seller’s browser path.
The Equifax breach became infamous partly because the vulnerable software had a patch available, which made the public lesson even more painful.
When an organisation stores highly sensitive data, unpatched internet-facing systems are less a technical issue and more a leadership confession.
The Target breach is often cited because attackers reportedly pivoted via a third-party supplier, making vendor risk everyone’s least glamorous but most persistent problem.
Third-party access is useful until it becomes the bit in the post-incident review where everyone discovers how broad it really was.
The Yahoo breaches were historically notable not just for scale, but for how long compromise can live in an environment before the damage is fully understood.
Breach size is often the fact journalists remember, but dwell time is the detail defenders fear more.
APT1, documented by Mandiant in 2013, helped drag public discussion of state-linked intrusion groups into the mainstream with unusually detailed reporting.
Naming threat groups has become its own folklore, which is why the same actor can appear to have several identities depending on whose slide deck you opened.
Fancy Bear, Cozy Bear, Sandworm, Lazarus and friends are memorable names for groups doing extremely unmemorable things to international stability.
Sandworm is closely associated with some of the most disruptive operations in modern cyber conflict, including attacks on Ukrainian infrastructure.
The 2015 and 2016 attacks on parts of Ukraine’s grid showed that cyber operations can cross the line from espionage into direct infrastructure disruption.
Grid attacks also remind defenders that industrial and operational technology environments cannot be secured with good intentions and a quarterly awareness poster.
BlackEnergy became associated with Ukraine infrastructure intrusions, proving once again that malware names alternate between comic-book villain and obscure metal band.
Industroyer and Industroyer2 were built to interact with industrial protocols, which is the sort of sentence that makes OT defenders age in real time.
When malware understands field protocols, the attack surface stops being abstract and starts looking a lot more like switches, breakers, and real-world consequences.
Lazarus Group is tied to both espionage and financially motivated operations, which is a reminder that state-linked activity and profit are not always separate lanes.
The Bangladesh Bank heist showed how attackers could abuse SWIFT-related processes to attempt massive fraudulent transfers without needing a Hollywood keyboard scene.
One of the most memorable details from that heist was that some transfers were reportedly interrupted partly by spelling errors, which is almost insulting.
Attackers have repeatedly abused legitimate admin tools like PowerShell, PsExec, and WMI, turning ordinary operations into forensic camouflage.
The phrase living off the land exists because defenders noticed that using built-in tools is often quieter than dropping obvious malware.
LOLBins are not malicious in themselves; they are just legitimate binaries that attackers borrow because blending in beats standing out.
If a process is signed, built in, and widely used, attackers will eventually try to hide inside it. Convenience is a two-way street.
PowerShell became both a defender favourite and an attacker favourite, which is a common fate for tools powerful enough to save time.
Script interpreters are useful because they automate good administration; they are dangerous for exactly the same reason.
WMI abuse appears in countless intrusion write-ups because remote execution and system interrogation remain attractive when stealth and reach both matter.
Attackers love persistence mechanisms that look boring, because boring is what busy teams overlook.
Scheduled tasks, registry run keys, services, startup folders, and remote tools remain popular because they work, even if they are older than some analysts.
A surprising amount of intrusion detection is just learning all the normal weirdness in your estate before someone adds malicious weirdness on top.
Phishing remains effective not because users are foolish, but because attackers iterate faster than most awareness programmes and only need one convincing moment.
Spearphishing differs from generic phishing mainly in the amount of homework done beforehand, which is why personalisation remains dangerous.
Business Email Compromise often uses no malware at all, which is offensively efficient and very annoying for teams that only trust detections with hashes.
BEC works because process weaknesses are still exploitable even when the endpoint protection graphs look healthy.
Invoice fraud, payroll diversion, and gift-card scams are low-glamour crime categories that keep thriving because urgency and authority still move money.
Gift-card fraud campaigns are the cyber equivalent of robbing a bank by pretending to be your boss and asking for a favour before lunch.
MFA fatigue attacks abuse repeated push notifications until a user approves out of confusion or exhaustion; social engineering has simply learned to vibrate.
MFA is hugely valuable, but like any control, it can be blunted if users are trained to accept friction rather than question it.
SIM swapping turns phone numbers into identity weak points by hijacking the recovery channel many services still trust too much.
Account recovery flows are often where strong authentication goes to be politely undermined.
Password spraying succeeds because many organisations still have enough predictable passwords to make low-and-slow guessing a reasonable business model.
Spraying differs from brute force by being more patient and less noisy, which is usually the part attackers appreciate most.
Long before deepfakes, social engineering relied on urgency, hierarchy, curiosity, fear, and goodwill; modern tooling just scales the same instincts.
Attackers do not need everyone to believe them, only the one person currently too busy to verify.
Smishing and vishing persist because people still trust phones and texts more than they probably should, especially when stress is involved.
Caller ID and email display names are examples of presentation layers humans over-trust; attackers noticed this years ago.
A fake login page only needs to look convincing for a few seconds, which is why defender perfection standards are usually unfair.
Browser padlock icons do not mean a site is trustworthy; they mean the connection is encrypted, which is helpful but not the same thing at all.
HTTPS secures the pipe, not the morals of the person at the other end.
Typosquatting works because the human visual system is surprisingly generous to domain names in a hurry.
Homograph attacks can abuse similar-looking characters to create deceptive domains, proving that Unicode is both a marvel and a menace.
Threat actors have repeatedly registered lookalike domains for brand impersonation, credential theft, and support scams because spelling is now part of attack surface management.
Fake browser updates and fake CAPTCHA lures remain depressingly effective because users have been trained to obey interface friction.
One modern trick is using CAPTCHA pages to make victims copy and paste commands, which is a crude but effective way to outsource initial access.
Ransomware crews increasingly operate like businesses, with affiliates, negotiations, support desks, and branding choices no sane person should admire.
Ransomware-as-a-service proved that cybercrime loves franchising when it reduces overhead and scales abuse.
Some ransomware groups publish “press release” style leak-site updates, because apparently even extortion wants content strategy.
Double extortion added data theft to encryption, making backups less of a silver bullet and more of one layer in a deeply irritating defence stack.
Triple extortion then added pressure on customers, partners, or staff, because criminals rarely stop once they find another lever.
A ransomware note promising “professional handling” is one of the more absurd language genres the internet has produced.
Ryuk, Conti, LockBit, BlackCat/ALPHV, Clop, and others helped define different phases of the ransomware era, each leaving defenders with new habits and fewer weekends.
Some big ransomware incidents began with very ordinary entry points like VPN compromise, phishing, or exposed remote access, which is not comforting but is useful.
Clop became especially prominent in file-transfer exploitation waves, showing how one software flaw can turn into a large-scale extortion conveyor belt.
Mass exploitation campaigns are why patch severity and threat relevance are not always identical; the internet votes very quickly.
MOVEit exploitation reminded organisations that “third-party file transfer” is not the same as “someone else’s problem”.
Secure file-sharing platforms are often trusted precisely because they handle sensitive data, which makes them attractive targets when they fail.
Zero-day means a vulnerability exploited before defenders have a patch or detection coverage ready, which is as rude as it sounds.
The book This Is How They Tell Me the World Ends helped pull the zero-day market into wider public conversation, where it remains unsettling reading.
A zero-click exploit is the security equivalent of being mugged by a message you never opened.
Mobile zero-click chains are so prized because they remove user dependency, and users have spent years being blamed for breaches already.
Pegasus spyware became globally infamous because it showed how advanced mobile surveillance tooling could target phones used by journalists, activists, and political figures.
Mobile phones are now identity hubs, camera systems, document stores, second-factor devices, and constant network beacons, which is why compromising one is such a rich prize.
The average corporate phone quietly carries more authority than some on-prem servers did twenty years ago.
Rootkits are designed to hide, which makes them less about dramatic break-in and more about long-term deception.
Bootkits take that idea lower into the startup chain, because some attackers prefer persistence before the operating system has fully woken up.
Firmware attacks matter because reinstalling the OS does not help much if the malware moved into the walls.
UEFI security became a bigger conversation once defenders realised pre-OS trust anchors are both powerful and annoyingly complicated.
The lower in the stack an attacker gets, the fewer normal tools can see them clearly.
Kernel-level compromise is usually bad news because the system is effectively being watched by something sitting under the guards.
Attackers often disable or tamper with security tools first, because no one likes witnesses.
Process injection remains common because reusing a trusted process beats launching something obviously unfamiliar.
Credential dumping from memory became infamous through tools like Mimikatz, which taught a generation of defenders to care a great deal about LSASS.
Many identity attacks are less about cleverness and more about harvesting what a user or admin session has already made available.
Pass-the-hash is one of those concepts that sounds niche until you realise it turns authentication leftovers into movement rights.
Pass-the-ticket and Kerberos abuse taught defenders that identity protocols are lovely right up until attackers understand them too.
Golden Ticket attacks abuse Kerberos trust so completely that the name sounds almost whimsical until you are the one rotating krbtgt.
Active Directory is often described as the crown jewel because it controls so much; unfortunately, that description is also excellent attacker marketing.
AD misconfigurations are often old, inherited, undocumented, and deeply trusted, which is why they survive long enough to matter.
Privileged groups that accreted members over years often look less like access control and more like sedimentary rock.
“Temporary admin” has a strange tendency to become permanent unless someone keeps receipts.
Attack path tools became popular because visualising compounded privilege is easier than reading three hundred nested group memberships and pretending that is governance.
Kerberoasting works by abusing service tickets for offline cracking, which is a neat example of normal protocol behaviour becoming a hunting ground.
A very strong domain with a few weak service account passwords is not, in fact, very strong.
Service accounts have historically been given exactly the qualities attackers enjoy most: high privilege, infrequent rotation, and very little curiosity from humans.
Lateral movement is often where defenders first spot an intrusion, not because initial access is invisible, but because post-compromise behaviour gets greedier.
Remote admin traffic at the wrong time from the wrong host using the wrong account remains one of the most useful flavours of “that’s odd”.
Data exfiltration does not always look dramatic; sometimes it is just well-timed archive creation, cloud upload, and enough bandwidth to regret not watching sooner.
Compression tools are not malicious, but a server suddenly zipping its best possessions before an outbound transfer is worth a raised eyebrow.
Attackers frequently use commodity cloud services for staging or exfiltration because defenders are reluctant to block everything with a recognisable logo.
DNS tunnelling turns a foundational protocol into a covert channel, because attackers love hiding in traffic everyone depends on.
DNS is one of the internet’s most trusted systems, which means abuse there tends to linger until someone asks unusually good questions.
Domain fronting and related evasions have shown how shared infrastructure can complicate blocking when innocent and malicious traffic look socially connected.
Attackers often test multiple persistence mechanisms because they know defenders usually find one and congratulate themselves a bit too soon.
Incident responders eventually learn that “eradicated” and “quiet” are not synonyms.
A useful threat hunting question is not “do we have this IOC?” but “what behaviour would this intrusion force somewhere in our telemetry?”
Good hunts are hypothesis-led; bad hunts are usually “search everything for vibes”.
Detection engineering is partly the art of turning suspicious behaviour into logic without turning the SOC into a false-positive support group.
The best detections are often boringly specific rather than theatrically broad.
A SIEM can centralise logs, but it cannot centralise judgement. People still have to care about what they are seeing.
Security telemetry ages badly if no one tests it against real attacker behaviour; shelfware is not a control.
Endpoint detection changed blue-team practice because visibility into process trees, command lines, and module loads is often where stories become solvable.
The process tree is one of the best gifts defenders were ever given, largely because attackers keep leaving family clues.
Script block logging, PowerShell transcription, AMSI, and command-line telemetry have all been battlegrounds because visibility hurts attacker comfort.
AMSI bypasses exist because attackers noticed defenders finally had a flashlight somewhere useful.
“Living off the land” often really means “we noticed your environment already contains our toolkit if we rename the intent”.
YARA rules became beloved because they give defenders a flexible way to describe suspicious file traits without needing exact signatures for everything.
Sigma rules became popular because detection content that can travel between platforms saves teams from rewriting the same logic in six dialects and a bad mood.
MITRE ATT&CK gave the industry a shared vocabulary for adversary behaviour, which in turn gave slide decks a lot more boxes to colour in.
ATT&CK is most useful when it informs actual detection and hunt coverage, not when it is used as decorative wallpaper for maturity claims.
A beautifully mapped matrix with weak logging behind it is still just a confidence costume.
IOC feeds are helpful, but behaviour survives infrastructure churn better than IP addresses do.
Attackers can rotate domains faster than most change boards rotate meeting minutes.
TTPs matter because even when tools change, habits often leave familiar fingerprints.
Threat intelligence is useful when it narrows decisions, not when it becomes a scrapbook of cyber misery.
In practice, a short intel note that changes one hunt or one detection can be more valuable than fifty pages of context nobody operationalises.
Hashes are precise but brittle; behaviours are noisier but age better. Pick your pain.
The “dwell time” metric became famous because long-running intrusions are usually not the result of one missed alert, but of many missed chances to connect signals.
Mean time to detect and mean time to respond are useful, but they are also statistics very capable of flattering weak reality if the scoping is kind enough.
Red teams are useful partly because defenders rarely discover monitoring blind spots by admiring themselves.
Purple teaming works best when the goal is improved coverage, not theatrical compromise for a screenshot and a biscuit afterwards.
Security awareness posters without process change are basically decorative guilt.
Users behave better when the secure path is easier than the insecure workaround, which is not weakness; it is ergonomics.
Shadow IT often appears because approved IT is too slow, too hard, or too disconnected from real work. Attack surface has user-experience roots.
Security teams that only say “no” often end up learning about risky workarounds after the workaround becomes an incident.
Least privilege sounds obvious until you try removing access from systems that have quietly depended on “temporary” exceptions for years.
Privilege creep is what happens when access is granted as a courtesy and reviewed as a rumour.
The principle of separation of duties exists because fraud and misuse get harder when one person cannot both approve and execute the bad idea.
Data classification matters because defending “everything equally” is the quickest route to protecting nothing especially well.
Backups only count if you can restore from them, and restore testing is where many backup strategies discover they were actually hopeful filing systems.
Offline or immutable backups became far more fashionable once ransomware crews started deleting or encrypting the obvious copies first.
A backup console with the same admin credentials as production is less a recovery plan and more a shared destiny.
“Single pane of glass” is a phrase often heard shortly before someone discovers the pane has a crack exactly where the incident is hiding.
PCI DSS, HIPAA, GDPR, NIS2, and similar frameworks matter, but compliance and security are related, not identical species.
Passing an audit does not prove resilience; it proves you successfully met a standard on a date. Attackers are rarely impressed by dates.
Secure coding starts with input validation, least privilege, and sane defaults, all of which sound sensible and still get skipped under deadline pressure.
Buffer overflows are older than many modern stacks and yet still matter because memory safety has never been a problem you can ignore into extinction.
SQL injection remains legendary because it is conceptually simple, often devastating, and an eternal reminder not to trust user input.
If user input can change query structure, you are not processing data; you are inviting improvisation.
Cross-site scripting matters because browsers trust websites to behave, and websites sometimes repay that trust very creatively.
XSS has outlived countless redesigns because “displaying untrusted content safely” remains more fiddly than many teams hope.
CSRF taught developers that authenticated browsers can be tricked into doing work on behalf of users who never meant to ask.
Session management bugs are dangerous because identity on the web often lives or dies through tokens, cookies, and expiry decisions made under deadline.
SSRF became a cloud-era favourite because internal metadata services turned “fetch a URL for me” into “please steal my credentials if you know the path”.
Cloud changes old assumptions about trust; internal does not always mean safe when workloads are one request away from impersonation.
Deserialisation bugs proved that turning complex objects back into live code paths is fantastic until someone sends you a poisoned object.
Log4Shell became instantly infamous because a widely used Java logging library turned routine string handling into remote code execution at terrifying scale.
Log4Shell was the sort of vulnerability that made defenders revisit the phrase “just a library” with visible pain.
Software composition matters because many organisations do not actually know what they are running until a critical CVE introduces them.
An SBOM can be useful, but only if someone reads it before the next emergency, not while actively panicking during it.
Heartbleed showed that a tiny bounds-checking mistake in a foundational crypto library could expose memory contents from systems all over the internet.
Heartbleed was a reminder that open source can be both indispensable and under-resourced, which is not a healthy pairing for core infrastructure.
Shellshock made environment variables briefly terrifying to much wider audiences than usual.
Bash unexpectedly becoming headline material was funny only for people not patching everything in sight.
Dirty COW became a memorable Linux privilege escalation because kernel race conditions have a talent for sounding cute and behaving badly.
EternalBlue is a case study in why patched-but-unapplied is not a state defenders should celebrate.
Vulnerability management is not just severity sorting; it is deciding which flaws are likely to matter in your environment before attackers answer for you.
“Critical” on a scanner and “critical to us” in practice are not always identical, which is why context keeps trying to join the meeting.
Exposure without exploitation is technical debt; exposure with active exploitation is usually a very short meeting followed by a long week.
Patch Tuesday exists because coordinating updates is better than chaos, although to many IT teams it still feels like scheduled chaos with branding.
Delayed patching is often blamed on complexity, legacy dependencies, or downtime risk, all of which are real right up until the exploitation notice arrives.
Virtual patching, compensating controls, and segmentation are not excuses to ignore a fix forever; they are what you do while reality catches up.
Segmenting networks is one of the least glamorous and most consistently useful ways to stop one compromise becoming everyone’s problem.
Flat networks are convenient until an attacker discovers they are, too.
Air gaps are not mythical shields if updates, removable media, engineering laptops, or trusted bridges can still move across the boundary.
Stuxnet is the famous example people cite whenever someone says an isolated network is automatically safe.
USB drives remain useful tools and enduring risk objects because “sneakernet” never truly retired.
BadUSB style attacks exploited the fact that a device can lie about what it is, which is philosophically rude and technically effective.
Hardware implants have made spy novels feel less silly, although still not quite as dramatic as conference keynotes.
TEMPEST and side-channel work showed long ago that systems can leak through timing, radiation, sound, and power, which is not comforting if you enjoy certainty.
Acoustic cryptanalysis has included researchers inferring information from keyboard sounds and device noise, proving paranoia occasionally earns overtime.
Side-channel attacks like Spectre and Meltdown showed that CPU performance tricks can create security consequences at the architecture level.
Spectre and Meltdown were especially unsettling because they turned fundamental processor behaviour into a security conversation for almost everyone at once.
Microarchitectural bugs are horrible partly because patching them often involves speed trade-offs, and nobody likes choosing between safe and fast in production.
Rowhammer demonstrated that repeatedly accessing memory rows could induce bit flips, which is about as impolite as hardware attacks get.
Hardware security is often invisible right up until the firmware update notes become the scariest reading of the quarter.
TPMs and secure enclaves exist because key material does better when it is not casually hanging around in general memory.
A hardware root of trust is still only one part of trust; processes around provisioning, recovery, and admin access can still ruin the mood.
PGP made strong public-key encryption available to wider audiences, while also proving that usable key management is a social challenge wearing a mathematical hat.
Good cryptography is usually easy to praise and hard to deploy well because the weak point is often everything built around it.
Encryption protects data at rest and in transit; it does not protect a user already logged in as the attacker’s best friend.
End-to-end encryption secures content between endpoints, which is brilliant until someone compromises an endpoint and simply reads it there instead.
TLS is one of the quiet heroes of the internet because most people only notice it when it breaks or when someone forgets a certificate renewal.
Expired certificates have caused surprisingly public outages, proving once again that mundane operational failures can outsprint sophisticated threat models.
Public key infrastructure sounds elegant until you are actually managing issuance, trust stores, revocation, and certificate inventory in a large estate.
Browsers became some of the most important security platforms on earth because they sit at the meeting point of identity, code execution, and user optimism.
Browser extensions can be useful productivity aids or terrible ideas with permissions, depending on who wrote them and what they quietly update into later.
Malvertising showed that even legitimate ad ecosystems can become malware delivery paths when the supply chain gets messy enough.
Drive-by downloads made “I only visited a website” a perfectly valid incident opening line.
Security researchers have repeatedly shown that internet-connected toys, TVs, baby monitors, and appliances can be compromised, because vendors keep shipping tiny computers with very big assumptions.
The phrase Internet of Things often means “things we gave IP addresses before we gave them patch plans”.
Smart doorbells, cameras, fridges, and lightbulbs are excellent examples of attack surface migration disguised as convenience.
Internet-connected fish tank sensors became a famous anecdote because apparently even aquariums can end up in breach stories if network access is sloppy enough.
A “smart” device without update support tends to become merely “online”.
Industrial systems once benefited from obscurity and isolation; now that many are connected, they get the risks of IT without always getting the tooling.
OT defenders often have to protect assets that cannot be patched easily, rebooted casually, or replaced this budget cycle, which makes good architecture priceless.
Safety and security overlap in industrial environments, but they are not interchangeable; getting that wrong can produce very expensive lessons.
The CIA triad of confidentiality, integrity, and availability sounds academic until availability vanishes and everyone suddenly rediscovers the third word.
Integrity is often the underappreciated sibling until someone changes data or control logic while the system still looks healthy.
Availability incidents are sometimes treated as “just outages”, but a targeted disruption can matter more to operations than a quiet data leak.
BGP hijacks have shown that internet routing trust can be abused in ways that redirect or blackhole traffic far beyond the local administrator’s field of view.
DNS cache poisoning, route leaks, and certificate misuse all exploit the same old truth: distributed trust is powerful and brittle.
Cloud did not remove security work; it changed where mistakes are made and who can make them quickly.
Misconfigured cloud storage buckets became iconic because exposing sensitive data no longer required advanced malware, just permissive settings and bad luck.
The cloud shared-responsibility model is simple in theory and a source of many uncomfortable discovery calls in practice.
Identity is the new perimeter largely because workloads, users, SaaS, and remote access moved beyond neat network edges years ago.
If the perimeter is now identity, then poor identity hygiene is basically leaving the gate open and complimenting the hinges.
API security matters because modern applications talk through APIs constantly, and attackers are happy to join the conversation uninvited.
The OWASP Top Ten has changed over time, but insecure design and broken access control keep proving that fundamentals age better than frameworks.
Broken access control being common is especially frustrating because the app often works exactly as built; it just should not have been built that way.
Security through obscurity fails regularly, though obscurity plus real controls can buy time. Obscurity alone buys incident retrospectives.
Developers did not invent the phrase “works on my machine” as a security warning, but sometimes it lands there anyway.
DevSecOps became popular less because of buzzwords and more because bolting security on at the end kept generating expensive surprises.
Secret management is now a first-class problem because cloud-native systems can leak tokens, keys, and credentials with the speed of automation.
Hard-coded secrets in repositories remain a recurring breach theme because copying a file is easier than establishing a secure secret pipeline under deadline.
Commit history is where many secrets go to retire badly.
GitHub and other code platforms have repeatedly been mined by attackers looking for exposed tokens, credentials, and internal clues people forgot they published.
Open-source intelligence is powerful because organisations leak far more context than they think through documents, repos, metadata, and public infrastructure.
A public PDF can say more about your environment than a dozen threat intel reports if no one scrubbed the author fields and internal naming.
Metadata is one of those things defenders remember exists immediately after someone else finds it first.
Security misconfigurations often outnumber software exploits as practical risk because secure defaults are not as common as product pages suggest.
Default credentials have powered countless compromises because vendors keep shipping them and customers keep meaning to change them later.
“Later” is one of the internet’s most successful persistence mechanisms.
Honeypots and deception systems work because attackers do not always expect the environment to lie back.
A good decoy asset can save analysts time by turning unauthorised interaction into immediate suspicion instead of a long argument.
Attackers also use deception, from fake updates to fake support calls to fake captchas, so fair play was never really on the table.
Cybercrime forums have functioned as marketplaces, help desks, review boards, and recruitment channels, because criminal operations also suffer from quality control issues.
Reputation matters on underground forums too; even extortion ecosystems dislike getting scammed by their own suppliers.
Some ransomware crews have had internal drama, rebrands, leaks, or “retirements”, which makes them sound like bands if you ignore the crimes.
Leak sites are partly extortion tools and partly marketing, proving once again that the worst people also understand audience pressure.
Cryptocurrency made certain kinds of cybercrime easier to monetise across borders, but it did not remove the attacker’s favourite currency: access.
The hardest part of many investigations is not knowing whether a compromise is over, but whether the attacker still has one boring path left.
Incident reports often make attacks look linear; real intrusions are messier, with retries, mistakes, dead ends, and lucky breaks on both sides.
Attackers misconfigure things too, and defenders occasionally win because someone on the other side also works under pressure.
Some famous botnets and malware families have been partially sinkholed or dismantled because researchers and law enforcement found ways to seize infrastructure or redirect traffic.
Sinkholing is one of the more satisfying cyber concepts: redirecting malicious traffic into visibility instead of impact.
Threat actor operational security tends to erode over time as campaigns scale and more people touch the machinery.
Reused infrastructure, development mistakes, timezone clues, language artefacts, and test files have all contributed to attribution discussions that become very lively very quickly.
Attribution in cyber is difficult because spotting fingerprints is not the same as producing courtroom-grade certainty.
False flags are possible, but defenders should not let that excuse become a reason to ignore strong evidence entirely.
Security headlines love “sophisticated”, but many damaging intrusions still begin with very ordinary failures in patching, identity, configuration, or verification.
Most rainbow tables are less of a threat now against properly salted hashes, which is the rare case where doing the boring thing properly genuinely helps.
Hashing is not encryption, however many executives have used the terms interchangeably in meetings they should not have chaired.
A one-way cryptographic hash is meant for verification, while encryption is meant for secrecy; confusing them is common and occasionally catastrophic.
Salts make identical passwords produce different stored hashes, which is one of the reasons unsalted password databases age so badly after breach disclosure.
Password managers are popular with defenders because humans are not naturally good at generating or remembering dozens of unique, high-entropy secrets.
The strongest password policy in the world fails quickly if it drives users to seasonal patterns, desk notes, or creative password recycling.
Long passphrases work well partly because memorability and entropy do not have to be enemies if design is sensible.
Multi-factor authentication is one of the biggest easy wins in security, which is why attackers keep inventing ways to bypass, phish, downgrade, or fatigue it.
The rise of phishing-resistant MFA methods matters because shared secrets and push approvals were never going to be the final form.
FIDO and passkeys aim to reduce phishing risk by tying authentication to device-bound cryptography, which is refreshingly hostile to fake login pages.
Passwordless does not mean “no security problems”; it means a different set of recovery, device trust, and lifecycle problems you must actually think through.
User access reviews are tedious until you compare them with the excitement of discovering former interns still hold production permissions.
Joiners, movers, and leavers processes are security controls wearing HR clothing.
Dormant accounts are favourites for attackers because neglected identities often come with low scrutiny and broad opportunity.
Logs are only useful if they are retained, searchable, trusted, and mapped to the questions incident responders will actually need to ask.
Turning on every log without a plan mostly creates a very expensive future archaeology project.
Time sync matters in investigations because reconstructing an intrusion from unsynchronised systems is a special kind of punishment.
Good case notes during incidents feel slow in the moment and priceless when the incident review begins and everyone’s memory goes on holiday.
A post-incident review that ends at “user clicked link” is usually just an expensive way of refusing to learn anything structural.
Mature teams ask not only how the intrusion happened, but why speed bumps, detections, access limits, and recovery plans did not reduce the blast radius.
The phrase defence in depth sounds abstract until one control fails and the next one prevents the week becoming unmanageable.
Single points of failure are bad in engineering and worse in security, where they often come with admin rights and an undocumented service dependency.
Security culture is built less through slogans and more through whether reporting a suspicious event is easy, welcomed, and acted on quickly.
If staff think reporting an incident will get them blamed, many will wait, and attackers are deeply supportive of that atmosphere.
“Trust but verify” is still too generous for many modern workflows; “verify, then maybe trust briefly” is closer.
Attackers often exploit the gap between system trust and process trust; once one is broken, the other follows politely.
Security is often described as a journey because “unfinished but unavoidable with recurring surprise costs” tested badly with stakeholders.
The best cyber trivia often doubles as a lesson: the surprising detail is memorable, but the process failure is usually the part that repeats.
A weird but useful SOC habit is keeping a list of attack stories that sound ridiculous, because ridiculous things still happen in production on Tuesdays.
If an incident sounds too odd to be real, check it anyway; cyber history is full of cases that would have been rejected by an editor as unrealistic.
Stolen credentials are still among the most valuable resources in cybercrime because logging in normally is quieter than breaking in noisily.
Browser cookies and session tokens are prized because they can sometimes bypass the inconvenience of passwords and MFA entirely.
Infostealer malware has surged in relevance because stealing sessions, saved passwords, and crypto wallets can be monetised quickly and at scale.
Attackers increasingly pursue cloud identity and SaaS admin access because that is where modern business control often lives, not in a single server room.
A compromised email account with search, forwarding rules, and trust from colleagues is one of the most efficient fraud platforms in a company.
Suspicious inbox rules and stealthy auto-forwarding are classic examples of tiny changes with very outsized downstream consequences.
Mailbox compromise often becomes data theft, internal phishing, or payment fraud before it becomes malware, which is why email telemetry matters so much.
Security teams love “high signal” because buried analysts make poor detectives, and attackers benefit when every alert looks equally miserable.
Tuning detection logic is not glamorous, but neither is reading seven thousand low-value alerts to miss the one that mattered.
False positives cost attention, and attention is one of the few response resources you cannot quickly buy once the incident is live.
A good bulletin fact is not just trivia; it gives the reader a mental hook that makes later threat reporting stick faster.
Cyber history is useful because new attack packaging often sits on top of very old ideas: trust abuse, weak verification, shared secrets, and delayed patching.
The strongest lesson from decades of incidents is not that technology is doomed, but that mundane controls routinely outperform heroic storytelling.
If a security tale ends with “nobody thought anyone would do that”, it usually means someone confused inconvenience with defence.
The world of cyber security changes constantly, but one fact refuses to age: the boring fundamentals still ruin the most expensive attacker plans when organisations actually do them properly.
